# ossloop

A minimal, real loop-engineering harness — running entirely on a local
model (`gpt-oss:20b` via [Ollama](https://ollama.com)), no API key, no
cloud dependency.

"Loop engineering" here means: you run this once with a goal and a budget,
and the system prompts the model itself — proposing a change, executing
it, verifying it, deciding whether to continue — without you typing each
turn by hand.

## Repo structure

```
ossloop/
├── src/ossloop/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── state.py            # persistent memory (LOOP_STATE.md on disk)
│   ├── model_client.py     # thin wrapper around the Ollama chat API
│   ├── maker.py             # proposes + executes the next shell diff, loads skills
│   ├── verifier.py          # runs pytest, the objective ground truth
│   ├── checker.py           # separate strict call: is the goal actually met?
│   ├── loop.py               # orchestrates maker -> verifier -> checker -> state
│   └── cli.py                 # `python -m ossloop.cli` entry point
├── skills/
│   └── repo-conventions.md  # project knowledge loaded into the maker's prompt
├── connectors/
│   └── issue_tracker.py     # MCP-shaped stand-in tool (SQLite issue tracker)
├── scripts/
│   ├── run_loop.sh          # heartbeat — meant for cron
│   └── parallel_worktrees.sh # spawns isolated git worktrees, runs loops in parallel
├── examples/                 # runtime scratch space (gitignored, created on run)
├── tests/
│   └── test_state.py        # unit tests that don't need a live model
├── pyproject.toml
├── .gitignore
├── LICENSE
└── README.md
```

## File → loop-engineering primitive map

| Location | Primitive | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| `src/ossloop/loop.py` | The loop itself (`/goal`) | Orchestrates one full maker → verify → checker cycle, repeatedly, until done or budget exhausted |
| `src/ossloop/state.py` | Memory / state | `LOOP_STATE.md` inside the target repo — lets the loop resume after a crash |
| `skills/repo-conventions.md` | Skills | Loaded into the maker's prompt every iteration |
| `scripts/run_loop.sh` | Automations | The heartbeat, meant to be triggered by cron |
| `scripts/parallel_worktrees.sh` | Worktrees | Isolated `git worktree` checkouts, run in parallel |
| `connectors/issue_tracker.py` | Plugins / connectors | Fixed, small function surface the loop can call to touch a real system |
| `src/ossloop/maker.py` vs `src/ossloop/checker.py` | Sub-agents (maker/checker split) | Two separate model calls, different system prompts, different context |

## Setup

```bash
git clone <this-repo> ossloop && cd ossloop
python3 -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate
pip install -e ".[dev]"

ollama pull gpt-oss:20b
ollama serve      # usually already running as a background service
```

## Run one loop by hand

```bash
python3 -m ossloop.cli \
  --repo ./examples/test_repo \
  --goal "Create hello.py that prints 'hello loop engineering' and test_hello.py that verifies it via subprocess" \
  --max-iterations 6 \
  --max-seconds 600 \
  --skills ./skills
```

Every step is appended to `examples/test_repo/LOOP_STATE.md` as it happens.

## Run it as an actual heartbeat

```bash
chmod +x scripts/run_loop.sh
crontab -e
# */15 * * * * /full/path/to/ossloop/scripts/run_loop.sh >> /full/path/to/loop.log 2>&1
```

## Run two loops in parallel without collisions

```bash
chmod +x scripts/parallel_worktrees.sh
./scripts/parallel_worktrees.sh
```

Creates `examples/worktrees/feature-hello` and `examples/worktrees/feature-add`,
each a separate checkout of the same repo history, running independent
gpt-oss:20b loops concurrently.

## Run the tests that don't need a live model

```bash
pytest tests/
```

## Honest limitations of a local 20b model in this pattern

- **No token cost, but real GPU/CPU time cost** — `--max-seconds` matters
  more here than in a hosted setup.
- **The maker/checker split is weaker with one model.** Both calls are the
  same weights; the strict, low-temperature checker prompt and withholding
  the maker's reasoning recovers some independence, but a genuinely
  different (larger, or hosted) model as the checker is a stronger check
  if one is available — swap only `checker.py`'s `call_model` target.
- **20b models drift off the expected fenced-block format** more than
  larger ones; `maker.py`'s regex extraction falls back to raw text
  silently — watch the first few runs before trusting it unattended.
- **The filesystem is the only reachable "tool" until you add real
  connectors.** `connectors/issue_tracker.py` is a stand-in; swap it for
  an actual MCP server (Linear, GitHub Issues, Slack) to make the loop
  useful beyond editing files.
